        <h5>The Tools</h5>
        <ul>
          <li>Ruby on Rails</li>
          <li>Git Bash</li>
          <li>Adobe Creative Cloud</li>
          <li>Bootstrap</li>
          <li>Think-alouds</li>
        </ul><br>   
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-header">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3">
      <h1 class="text-center">techCorp</h1>
      <h4 class="text-center">A Responsive App for Sharing Technical Documents</h4>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-lg-4 col-lg-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('share-desk-mobile.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>A Responsive Form</h5>
          <p>Professors and Students can upload documents from desktop and mobile browsers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-6">
      <h3>My Process</h3>
      <h6>User-Centered Design</h6>
      <p>For the user interface, I adopted an iterative process to test and discover the best choices for uploading and  searching documents. From wireframing to prototype, professors and students helped test and develop the interface.</p>
      <h6>The Back-end</h6>
      <p>So that users could login and upload their technical documents, I took advantage of RESTful services such as Devise and Amazon Web Services&mdash;two popular services built for a Model, View, and Controller (MVC) framework such as Ruby on Rails.</p>
       
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">The Audience Analysis: Understanding the Client's Needs</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-lg-4 col-lg-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-audience.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>The Audience</h5>
          <p>Students would share documents for professors and other students to sort through and download.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Audience-Analysis</h3>
      <h6>The Clients and End-users</h6>
      <p>My goal was to learn about the needs of the clients of techCorp, a team of technical communication professors who wanted to develop an online corpus of technical documents produced by students. To ensure the database would meet the needs of the clients and users, I inquired about the following:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>How long will the system exist?</li>
        <li>What type of data may develop over time?</li>
        <li>What type of information will be entered?</li>
        <li>What type of people will interact with the database?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

  <div class="container-fluid conclusion-section">
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>The Analysis</h6>
      <p>I learned the professors had collected over 600 documents and stored descriptions for each document in an Excel sheet. The data included characteristics about the student, professor, the class, and the document itself.</p>
      <p>The users of the database would be students in higher education, researchers, and instructors. The group of users would be familiar with a research model similar to a library database. After choosing my tools, I would be ready to start the first iteration of the database.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  
<div class="container-fluid tc-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">Designing and Developing the Database</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4 database-image">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-iteration1.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Database Iteration One</h5>
          <p>Using object-relational mapping, I created models from my client's data to better understand how the data would be used in a Model, View, and Controller framework (MVC).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4 database-image">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-iteration2.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Database Iteration Three</h5>
          <p>Collaborating with techCorp clients, I realized the document object and its characteristics would remain constant and future metadata associations might be needed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4 database-image">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-schema.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Final Database Schema</h5>
          <p>Working with a PostgreSQL database, the document object was created as the model, <strong>corpus_entry</strong>, which included characteristics of the student, professor, and class.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Database Design</h3>
      <h6>Choosing the Right Tools</h6>
      <p>Using notepads, Visio, and the method of object-relational mapping, I created a database schema that would operate quickly in a MVC framework. Essential to the client, the database would offer flexibility for additional models and growth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid conclusion-section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>The Final Database Schema</h6>
      <p>Using Ruby on Rails, a web application framework, I began developing the back-end of techCorp using the reliable and secure Heroku Postgres database. Cloud storage was provided by the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3).</p>
      <p>After successful testing of the model and data with the CRUD process (create, read, update, and delete), further web development on the back and front-end could begin.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
