</div>

<div class="container-fluid tc-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Creating Users and Permissions</h3>
      <h6>A Database of Users</h6>
      <p>Using the Devise authentication service, the web application prototype can register users, develop a contact list, and potentially reach out to researchers, professors, and students with incentives and updates.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-register-mockup.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Creating Users - Iteration One</h5>
          <p>Using the MVC authentication solution, Devise for Rails, the web application would allow users to sign up and upload a document.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-0">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-register.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Creating Users - Final Iteration</h5>
          <p>With clear options and instructions, the sign-up page was given the name <strong>Share</strong>, a likeable word that fits the core theme of the corpus.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Uploading a Document</h3>
      <h6>Interacting with Users</h6>
      <p>I developed the form with the guidance of usability principles and user-feedback. Using think-aloud testing, participants helped guide the order and structure of the form fields. For instance, select options were used to help the user quickly and confidently make entries.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-1 form-image">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('form-mockup.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Building the Form</h5>
          <p>Understanding how best to organize and group the fields of the form, mockups and user-testing were both utilized. Participants included both students and techCorp clients.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-0 form-image">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-form.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>A User-tested Design</h5>
          <p>The Corpus Entry form was divided into three sections with the upload document button positioned last, allowing the user to experience the data and document file as simultaneously saved.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid conclusion-section">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>User-centered Web Development</h6>
      <p>With the needs of the client and user driving the development, the points of interaction with the end-user became the highest priorities, such as:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ease of use,</li>
        <li>Confidence in the system,</li>
        <li>A responsive design, and</li>
        <li>User-friendly copy.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The listed priorities were accomplished with both web technologies and user feedback. The MVC framework allowed for rapid uploads, Devise authentication created security for the user, Bootstrap structured a mobile-friendly responsive design, and user-feedback benefited the structure, organization, and experience of uploading a document to the corpus.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

